# karya

**Offline autonomous agent for low-power hardware.**  
Runs on Raspberry Pi, cheap VPS, old laptops — no internet, no cloud, no user input once started.

```
sensor/event → model decides → hardware acts
      ↑                              ↓
      └──────── world state ─────────┘
```

## What it does

karya wakes up on a configurable interval, reads the current system state,
asks a local LLM what to do, and executes the decision — shell commands, file
writes, GPIO control. It runs forever, completely offline, guided only by the
goals you define in `goals.yaml`.

No Hermes Agent overhead. No neural compression. No second LLM call just to
summarize. Pure rule-based context management tuned for tiny hardware.

---

## Hardware requirements

| Device | RAM | Model used | Tokens/sec |
|--------|-----|-----------|------------|
| Pi Zero 2W | 512MB | tinyllama:1.1b | 2–4 |
| Pi 4 (4GB) | 4GB | qwen2.5:1.5b | 8–12 |
| Pi 4/5 (8GB) | 8GB | qwen2.5:3b | 4–7 |
| Pi 5 (16GB) | 16GB | qwen2.5:7b | 2–4 |

karya auto-detects your hardware tier on startup and sets context budgets accordingly.

---

## Install

```bash
# 1. Install Ollama
curl -fsSL https://ollama.com/install.sh | sh

# 2. Pull a model (auto-recommended based on your RAM)
ollama pull qwen2.5:1.5b

# 3. Install karya
pip install karya          # or: pipx install karya

# 4. Check everything works
karya doctor
```

---

## Quickstart

```bash
# Edit your goals
nano config/goals.yaml

# Dry run — see decisions without executing
karya run-once --dry-run

# Start the autonomous loop
karya start

# Check current world state
karya status

# Benchmark inference speed on your hardware
karya bench
```

---

## goals.yaml

This is how you give the agent its mission. No code changes needed.

```yaml
goals:
  - "keep disk usage below 85% — clean /tmp and logs if needed"
  - "restart nginx if it stops running"
  - "alert if CPU temperature exceeds 75°C"
  - "log system metrics every cycle to /var/log/karya/metrics.csv"

constraints:
  - "never delete files in /home or /etc"
  - "if unsure, log and skip"

cycle_interval_seconds: 30
dry_run: false
safe_gpio_pins: []

ollama:
  base_url: "http://localhost:11434"
  model: ""   # leave blank for auto-detect
```

---

## Run on boot (Raspberry Pi)

```bash
sudo cp systemd/karya.service /etc/systemd/system/
sudo systemctl enable karya
sudo systemctl start karya
sudo journalctl -u karya -f   # follow logs
```

---

## Architecture

```
karya/
├── core/
│   ├── hw_detect.py   # RAM probe → tier → token budgets
│   ├── state.py       # world state (JSON on disk, survives reboots)
│   ├── context.py     # sliding window, no LLM needed
│   ├── safety.py      # command guard rails
│   └── loop.py        # perception → decision → action
├── backends/
│   └── ollama.py      # streaming + 4-level tool call parser
├── tools/
│   ├── ShellTool      # safe shell execution
│   ├── FileTool       # read/write with path limits
│   └── SystemInfoTool # cpu/mem/disk/temp from /proc
├── triggers/          # (coming) gpio, serial, file_watch, cron
└── cli.py             # karya start/run-once/doctor/status/bench
```

**Context management** — no neural summarization. Pure rule-based:
1. Truncate tool results first (biggest, lowest value)
2. Drop oldest turn pairs together
3. Shorten system prompt if needed
4. Hard truncate current message as last resort

**Tool call parsing** — 4-level fallback for small models that break JSON:
1. Native JSON parse
2. Extract from ```json block
3. Regex on bare JSON object
4. Keyword detection in plain text

